'''Baruch Solomon Löwenstein''' (born in mid-nineteenth century, [[Włodarka]], [[Russia]]) was a [[Jewish]] mathematician. He wrote ''Bikkure ha-Limmudiyyot'', explanations of mathematical passages in the works of [[Abraham ibn Ezra]], [[Moses Maimonides]], and [[Joseph Delmedigo]]. He also annotated and published in 1863 a second edition of ''Shebile di-Reḳia'', by Elias ben Ḥayyim Kohen Höchheimer, on the rules of the calendar, with the elements of geometry, trigonometry, and astronomy.<ref>{{Cite Jewish Encyclopedia|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/10149-lowenstein-baruch-solomon|title=Löwenstein, Baruch Solomon|first1=Gotthard|last1=Deutsch|first2=S.|last2=Mannheimer}}</ref>

