{{Spanish name|González|Baz}}
'''Enriqueta González Baz y de la Vega''' (September 22, 1915 – December 22, 2002) was a Mexican mathematician, a founder of the Mexican Mathematical Society, and the first woman to earn a degree in mathematics in Mexico.{{r|gdl|mim}}

After finishing secondary school, her father sent her two a two-year program in domestic studies, where one of the teachers, Elena Picazo de Murray, recognized her talent. She studied in a night school at the [[San Ildefonso College]], earned a teaching credential at the Escuela Nacional de Maestros, and completed a bachelor's degree in mathematical and physical sciences at the [[Escuela Nacional Preparatoria]] of the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico]]. She wrote a thesis on [[special functions]], and did additional postgraduate study at [[Bryn Mawr College]].{{r|mim}}

She became a mathematics professor in the Escuela Nacional Preparatoria, as well as holding several other associated positions. Among her mathematical works, she translated [[Solomon Lefschetz]]'s 1930 textbook ''Topology''.{{r|mim}}

